<h2> Academic Stuff </h2>

I am currently a PhD Student in <!WA5><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/">Computer Science</a>
at <!WA6><a href="http://www.jhu.edu/">the Johns Hopkins University</a> in <!WA7><a href = "http://www.charm.net/Baltimore.html">Baltimore, MD</a>.
I am blessed with not one, not two, but three advisers, <!WA8><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~kasif">Simon Kasif</a>,
<!WA9><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~brill">Eric Brill</a>,
and <!WA10><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~yarowsky/">David Yarowsky</a>.
While my general interest is in <!WA11><a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/Web/Groups/AI/html/repository.html">Artificial Intelligence</a>, the focus of my research is
on adaptive methods for Information Retrieval.
<P>
I've compiled a <!WA12><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~weiss/ir.html">Survey of Information Retrieval</a> which
lists many different papers, projects, and web sites devoted to various 
aspects of IR. If you're just learning about the field, be sure to check
out my <!WA13><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~weiss/glossary.html">glossary</a>.
<p>
I am also extremely interested in teaching.
<P>
<hr>
<h2> Personal Interests </h2>
<P>
I am a huge fan of games and puzzles of any type.
I've made up a <!WA14><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~weiss/puzzles.html">page</a> giving some of my favorite
sites and presenting puzzles that I've created. If you're a fan of Monopoly,
check out my expansion <!WA15><a href="http://www.cs.jhu.edu/~weiss/powers-monop.html">Powers Monopoly</a>.
